/* ============================================================
   GUEST: Sterling Crane — "The Secret History Salesman"
   NF STANDARD: 20 segments per playthrough. First 5 = INTRO RUNWAY.
   FAILURE MODEL v2 (heat/rapport -> endings, never mid-run death).
   ------------------------------------------------------------
   TRAIT MECHANIC (G80 P35 F25 H40): grandiose + slippery, WANTS TO DODGE.
     - PLAY ALONG is the TRAP move -> he converts agreement into a
       sales funnel. Rapport rises, but he's performing, not revealing.
       The audience gets hype; the host gets nothing real.
     - PUSH BACK is the PIN -> direct challenge catches him mid-dodge,
       forces a real sentence. He respects it grudgingly. Best material
       comes from being cornered. Hype soars.
     - STEER is the OTHER PIN -> a sideways question slips past his
       defenses. Gets genuine answers he didn't plan to give. The
       grandfather, the real fear, the private doubt.
     - DEADPAN holds his own pitch up as a mirror -> he sees himself
       in the silence and drops freebies, confessions, moments of real.
       Low hype, high yield.
   The art with Crane: don't let him sell. Every agreement is a funnel;
   every pin is a real sentence. The knife's edge: is he a fraud who
   stumbled onto something real, or a real one who got rich pretending
   to be a fraud? He doesn't know either. The seam page is genuine and
   he's spent thirty years cheapening it with a workshop.

   A single path walks 20 nodes:
     INTRO (5): arrive, thepitch, theproduct, thegrandfather, thedeal
     ARC (13): one of three:
       THE CALENDAR  cal_*  (engage the theory: the missing days, the math)
       THE EVIDENCE  evi_*  (engage the debunking: trees, eclipses, cascades)
       THE SALESMAN  sal_*  (engage the man: the origin, the fear, the act)
     CONVERGENCE: show_it (show the seam page live?) -> endings
     ENDINGS: end_real / end_pitch (+ busted/walkout hooks)

   RESEARCH WOVEN IN (fictionalized): Heribert Illig's phantom time
   hypothesis (297 years fabricated, AD 614-911); the Gregorian calendar
   10-day vs 13-day argument (Council of Nicaea 325 AD, not 45 BC);
   dendrochronology (continuous Irish/German oak chronologies through the
   'phantom' period); astronomical refutation (Pliny's 59 AD eclipse,
   Halley's Comet, Tang dynasty records); the cascading-fabrication problem
   (erasing Europe = erasing Byzantium + Islam + China + India); Romanesque
   architecture 'too good for its age'; Carolingian minuscule; Fomenko's
   New Chronology (the even-more-extreme version); manuscript traditions
   (Beowulf, Book of Kells); the psychology of conspiratorial grifting.
============================================================ */
